The implementation shall use protocol-agnostic traffic characterization by extracting generic packet, flow, timing, size, and statistical features instead of relying on any specific protocol. This enables the framework to generalize across all network traffic types.

the complete PCAP file represents the final input. Chunking is only an internal processing technique used for very large PCAP files to reduce memory usage and improve scalability. The final diagnosis is generated by combining the analysis of all processed chunks into a single output.

The implementation will generate a consolidated dashboard-style output directly in the terminal or application interface, displaying all important traffic statistics, detected issues, and diagnostic summaries without requiring users to open additional files.

Every implementation step will include simple explanations, algorithm descriptions, mathematical reasoning where applicable, and commented source code so that the complete workflow is easy to understand and reproduce.

The implementation will extend the existing project structure wherever possible, preserving its workflow while adding the proposed scalable network characterization and LLM-based diagnostic capabilities.

Python 3.11 is sufficient when combined with efficient packet parsing, streaming processing, chunk-based execution, optimized data structures, and parallel processing where appropriate. The design focuses on scalability rather than loading the complete PCAP into memory.

Metrics for scientific publication: 

Number of PCAP Chunks Vs. Processing Time (s)
This metric represents the total processing time required to analyze the entire PCAP file as the number of internally processed chunks increases.

Number of PCAP Chunks Vs. Throughput (MB/s)
The throughput refers to the aggregated processing throughput, calculated as the total size of the processed PCAP data divided by the total analysis time (MB/s). It measures processing efficiency rather than network bandwidth.

Number of PCAP Chunks Vs. Memory Utilization (MB)
Memory utilization is not derived from the PCAP itself. Instead, it measures the application's runtime memory consumption while processing the PCAP, providing an indication of computational efficiency.

Number of PCAP Chunks Vs. CPU Utilization (%)
This evaluates the computational efficiency of the processing framework.

Number of PCAP Chunks Vs. Anomaly Detection Accuracy (%)
Rather than detecting predefined cyberattacks, the framework identifies abnormal traffic behavior using protocol-agnostic statistical features such as packet rate, flow duration, packet size distribution, byte volume, inter-arrival time, and connection patterns. The LLM uses these summarized characteristics to generate diagnostic observations instead of performing signature-based intrusion detection.
